Incident Response > [T3]: Network Perimeter-level Detection

Detection Levels

There are many common aspects between military equipment and cyber security tools. Armies use radar systems to detect intrusions, similar to how an IDS is used inside the network. For a radar system to work, it has to be deployed in a way that meets operational requirements.

Check out the following quote from Blighter, a military radar systems manufacturer, talking about their A422 military radar:

"The flexibility of the new A422-based military radar system means that it is perfectly suited for use in rough or mountainous terrain as well as in urban environments, allowing it to be used for agile border security and rapid response situations such as battlefield reconnaissance or search and rescue operations."

Figure 1

Security is no different! We have to plan where to place our detections if we want them to perform well and deliver the expected output. From a bird's-eye view, there are four levels where we can detect attacks:

  • Network perimeter level: a threat is entering or leaving the network perimeter, such as a firewall detecting DOS and data exfiltration attacks.
  • Endpoint perimeter level: a threat is entering or leaving the endpoint perimeter, such as endpoint EDR detecting pivoting from one endpoint to another inside the same network.
  • Endpoint system level: a threat targets the endpoint without leaving its perimeter, such as an AntiVirus detecting a malware execution.
  • Application-level: a threat targets an application running on a server, such as a SIEM detecting web server authentication bypass logs.


The categorization you see above emphasizes the concept of Defense in Depth we discussed earlier. Your detections should be layered to provide a fall-back mechanism and increase the odds of catching attacks at different stages.

Let's start with network perimeter level detection!

 

Network Perimeter Level Detection

There are multiple log sources offering detection visibility on the network level, such as:

  • Network Firewalls: firewalls are the defacto standard network security tools. Although mainly considered a preventive control, firewalls blocked threats provide a great deal of context during the analysis phase. Regardless of the attack source and destination, the attack traffic will hit the firewall at some point.

    In addition, some blocked connection attempts are of high interest to the incident response team. For example, a connection originating from your network DMZ towards the internal network is abnormal activity. DMZ hosts organizations' services that will be accessed from the internet, such as organization web/mail servers. Connections from DMZ to LAN should instantly be flagged for immediate investigation.
     
  • Network IDS and IPS: No doubt that your network intrusion detection/prevention system is one of the most critical components of your detection arsenal. It can detect a broad spectrum of attacks regardless of the attack target. For example, a network IPS/IDS can detect a web application attack headed toward your web server, ransomware spreading from one compromised machine to another, or malware on an endpoint communicating with its command and control server. Suricata, the popular open-source IDS, is widely used to provide network-level detection.
     
  • Network Traffic Flows: A network flow is a stream of packets carrying information between two hosts and can be represented in the format of Source IP, Source Port, Destination IP, Destination port, and size of exchanged data. 

    A flow does not contain the data sent in the session, only the flow/connection information, making it easy to store a massive number of flow records. Routers and other networking devices can provide network flow information to detect data exfiltration and other malicious activities. For example, a flow originating from the internal network towards the internet with GIGs of data sent out indicates data exfiltration. You may find it helpful to check the white paper I wrote earlier about using Bro (now known as Zeek), a widespread network security tool to detect attack patterns in network traffic. 

 

In the following lesson, we will see how we can use Suricata to detect attacks on the network level. Then, we will explore the remaining detection levels.
